    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1974-11-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1974-11-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="274"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d274">
                <head>274. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for Economic Affairs (<persName
                        corresp="#p_SLW1" type="from">Seidman</persName>) to President <persName
                        corresp="#p_FGR1" type="to">Ford</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d274fn1">Source: <persName corresp="#p_FGR1"
                            >Ford</persName> Library, National Security Adviser, Presidential
                        Subject File, Box 6, Food (3). No classification marking. Sent by <persName
                            corresp="#p_SLW1">Seidman</persName> on behalf of <persName
                            corresp="#p_SWE1">Simon</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_AR1"
                            >Ash</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_GA1">Greenspan</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_EW1">Eberle</persName>, and <persName
                            corresp="#p_CKR1">Cole</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1974-11-08">November 8, 1974</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> Memo (11–6–74) re World
                        Food Conference Follow-up<note n="2" xml:id="d274fn2">
                            <ref target="#d273">Document 273</ref>.</note>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>Secretary <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> has proposed formation
                    of an International Food Review Group to follow-up on the World Food Conference
                        (<gloss target="#t_WFC1">WFC</gloss>). Secretary <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                        >Kissinger</persName>’s memorandum raises the principal question of who
                    should have the basic responsibility for food policy—a domestic policy oriented
                    group or a foreign policy oriented group.</p>
                <p>The important issues from the <gloss target="#t_WFC1">WFC</gloss> will include
                    food aid, grain reserves, trade negotiations, and domestic food policy. These
                    issues appropriately have been handled by the Economic Policy Board (<gloss
                        target="#t_EPB1">EPB</gloss>) and, to assure the continuity of our efforts
                    in the context of our overall economic objectives, they should continue to be
                    handled by the <gloss target="#t_EPB1">EPB</gloss>.</p>
                <p>The cabinet-level International Food Review Group proposed by Secretary <persName
                        corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> would result in an unnecessary
                    proliferation of decision-making groups. When addressing World Food Conference
                    follow-up issues, the Executive Committee of the <gloss target="#t_EPB1"
                        >EPB</gloss> will include representatives from State, Agriculture, <gloss
                        target="#t_STR1">STR</gloss>, and the NSC. This group would be identical to
                    the group proposed by Secretary <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                    >Kissinger</persName>.</p>
                <p>Given the importance of food policy issues, the Executive Committee also decided
                    that the Food Deputies Group will meet and report weekly to the Executive
                    Committee, and that <persName corresp="#p_SG1">Gary Seevers</persName> will <pb
                        facs="0989" n="958" xml:id="pg_958"/> continue as Chairman. If there is a
                    need for a separate working group to focus on follow-up <gloss target="#t_WFC1"
                        >WFC</gloss> issues, such a group should be established by <persName
                        corresp="#p_SG1">Gary Seevers</persName> and should report to him. The
                    working group proposed by Secretary <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                        >Kissinger</persName> does not provide for representation of Treasury,
                        <gloss target="#t_OMB1">OMB</gloss>, and <gloss target="#t_CEA1"
                    >CEA</gloss>, agencies which should have an input at the working level.</p>
                <p>The institutional arrangements recommended above are consistent with current
                    decisions on policy responsibilities, avoid the creation of unnecessary groups,
                    and allow all the concerned agencies to properly coordinate their inputs.</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="italic">Recommendation</hi>
                </p>
                <p>That the World Food Conference follow-up be handled under <gloss target="#t_EPB1"
                        >EPB</gloss> supervision and that you not establish an International Food
                    Review Group as proposed in the subject memorandum.<note n="3" xml:id="d274fn3"
                        >The President did not indicate his approval or disapproval of the
                        recommendation, but see <ref target="#d273fn3">footnote 3, Document
                            273</ref>.</note>
                </p>
            </div>
